04801nam a22006135i 9780804788953DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202013cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2013028176  a97808047889537 a10.1515/97808047889532doi  a(DE-B1597)563750  a(OCoLC)1198929848  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHV640.5.P36bA45 2014 4aHV640.5.P36bA45 2014eb 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a305.892/74056922231 aAllan, Diana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRefugees of the Revolution :bExperiences of Palestinian Exile /cDiana Allan. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on transliteration and translations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Commemorative economies -- t2. Economic subjectivity and everyday solidarities -- t3. Stealing power -- t4. Dream talk, futurity, and hope -- t5. Futures elsewhere -- t6. Many returns -- tConclusion: The roots of exile -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSome sixty-five years after 750,000 Palestinians fled or were expelled from their homeland, the popular conception of Palestinian refugees still emphasizes their fierce commitment to exercising their "right of return." Exile has come to seem a kind of historical amber, preserving refugees in a way of life that ended abruptly with "the catastrophe" of 1948 and their camps-inhabited now for four generations-as mere zones of waiting. While reducing refugees to symbols of steadfast single-mindedness has been politically expedient to both sides of the Arab-Israeli conflict it comes at a tremendous cost for refugees themselves, overlooking their individual memories and aspirations and obscuring their collective culture in exile. Refugees of the Revolution is an evocative and provocative examination of everyday life in Shatila, a refugee camp in Beirut. Challenging common assumptions about Palestinian identity and nationalist politics, Diana Allan provides an immersive account of camp experience, of communal and economic life as well as inner lives, tracking how residents relate across generations, cope with poverty and marginalization, and plan--pragmatically and speculatively-for the future. She gives unprecedented attention to credit associations, debt relations, electricity bartering, emigration networks, and NGO provisions, arguing that a distinct Palestinian identity is being forged in the crucible of local pressures. What would it mean for the generations born in exile to return to a place they never left? Allan addresses this question by rethinking the relationship between home and homeland. In so doing, she reveals how refugees are themselves pushing back against identities rooted in a purely nationalist discourse. This groundbreaking book offers a richly nuanced account of Palestinian exile, and presents new possibilities for the future of the community.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aIsrael-Arab War, 1948-1949xRefugeesxLebanon. 0aIsrael-Arab War, 1948-1949xRefugeeszLebanon. 0aPalestinian ArabsxSocial conditionsxLebanon. 0aPalestinian ArabszLebanonxSocial conditions. 0aRefugee campsxLebanon. 0aRefugee campszLebanon. 0aRefugees, Palestinian ArabxSocial conditionsxLebanon. 0aRefugees, Palestinian ArabzLebanonxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080478895340uh